<p>Blockquote</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I cannot get it to compile.  I get the error: “variable chassisSPeeds might not have been initialzed SwerveModuleState<span class="chcklst-box fa fa-square-o fa-fw"></span> moduleStates=DriveConstants.kDriveKinematics.toSwerveModuleStates(chassisSpeeds);”</p>
<p>Any help would be greatly appreciated because our driver has a tough time lining up to the 45 degree wall and makes collecting notes tough.</p>
<p>Also, as a side question because our robot is not driving no where near as smooth as these other robots here at the Fingerlakes Regional, does anyone have any recommendations on the fastest / most efficient way to tune <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> controller Constants / Coefficients for the Turing <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> controller for Swerve drive?</p>
<p>Thanks <span class="abbreviation">FRC<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="FIRST Robotics Competition"></template></span> Nation!</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":4,"updated_at":"2024-03-15T10:51:20.975Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":19,"reads":34,"readers_count":33,"score":101.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":458751,"topic_slug":"chassisspeeds-might-not-have-been-initialized-error","display_username":"mrmatheou","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":8656,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"post_url":"/t/chassisspeeds-might-not-have-been-initialized-error/458751/1","custom_user_title":null,"reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3333682,"name":"NewtonCrosby","username":"NewtonCrosby","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/n/ed8c4c/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-03-15T12:29:53.345Z","cooked":"<p>We don’t have a swerve so I don’t have any direct <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> tuning knowledge for swerve.  My recommendation there is to use smart dashboard to set the values so they can be constantly updated and tested.  WPILib docs show how to do that.<br>
With regard to <em>what</em> you’re tuning, I think that your steer motor probably follows under the principles of the <a href="https://docs.wpilib.org/en/stable/docs/software/advanced-controls/introduction/tuning-flywheel.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">flywheel tuning</a> article.</p>
<p>Basically, you need to have a good motion profile (with feed forward and feeback) to get to your steering angles efficiently.</p>
<p>As to the second question, your code will have have issues because you’re calling <strong>thread.sleep()</strong>.  That is bad news.</p>
<p>The robot is executing in a loop already with the scheduler, you should use that loop to check your state.  So, maybe use a <em><strong>Timer</strong></em> object from WPILib to count to 3 seconds to disable the functionality you’re looking for.</p>
<p>Lastly, if you just declare chassisSpeeds above your conditional things, you’ll get rid of the error.</p>
